===Glyph origin===
{{Han etyl}}
{{liushu|ic}}: two hands (now {{lang|zh|彐}} and {{lang|zh|寸}} ) stretched out measuring a mat (now {{lang|zh|工}}) – "a unit of measurement; [[arm span]]". The component {{zh-l|*口}} (“mouth, talk”) was likely added to emphasize the act of reading the measurement out loud. Forms with it have appeared as early as {{w|oracle bone script}}, but forms without it have also appeared as late as the {{w|Spring and Autumn period}}. 

Appears as {{zh-l|*𢒫}} in the Shuowen Jiezi, which interprets the character as {{liushu|psc|nocap=yes}} with {{och-l|彡}} as the sound component.

===Etymology 1===
{{zh-forms|s=寻|alt=㝷,𡬶,𢍟,𢒫,𱑵,𲇈,}}
; ''unit of length''; arm span
: From {{inh|zh|sit-pro|*s-la(ː)m|t=armspan; fathom; cord}} (STEDT). Cognate with {{cog|lus|hlam|t=measurement (armspan)}}, {{cog|my|လှမ်း|t=to reach out}}, {{m|my|လံ|t=fathom}}.
; to seek; to search
: Attested since the Eastern Han dynasty. {{rfe|zh}}

